Glassfrogs have a Neotropical distribution and are particularly diverse in the northern Andes. All centrolenids have a partial or complete ventral transparency, a dilated medial process on Metacarpal III, and deposit their eggs out of water (usually on the upper or under sides of leaves;
Hayes & Starrett 1980
;
Ruiz-Carranza & Lynch 1991
;
Guayasamin et al . 2009
). They are usually found at night on vegetation along streams when reproducing. Herein, we follow the taxonomy proposed by
Guayasamin et al . ( 2009 )
that recognizes 12 genera and 147 species within Centrolenidae . In YBS, there are five identified (
Centrolene bacatum , C. buckleyi , Nymphargus posadae , N. siren , N. wileyi
) and two unidentified (
Centrolene
sp,
Cochranella
sp) species of glassfrogs.

Remarks: Males of
Nymphargus posadae
collected in YBS are smaller (SVL = 30.7–31.9 mm , n = 3 ) than Colombian specimens (SVL = 32.7–34.1 mm , n = 3 ;
Ruiz-Carranza & Lynch 1995
;
Guayasamin et al. 2006 a
).
